ers tend to be [[spinster]]s who are strict disciplinarians.||\n''[[My Darling Clementine]]''\n|-\n| [[Scrooge]]|| A old, wealthy boss who refuses to spend money and prefers to hoard it. The character is based on the miserly, penny-pinching, and mean-spirited old [[Ebenezer Scrooge]] from ''[[A Christmas Carol]]''. Scrooge characters range from excessively thrifty, but otherwise benign types, to avaricious, cold-hearted types who are willing to allow harm to come to others.\n||J. Paul Getty in ''[[All the Money in the World]]'' , Randolph and Mortimer Duke in ''[[Trading Places]]'', Mister Potter from ''[[It's a Wonderful Life]]'', J. Jonah Jameson in the ''[[Spider-Man Trilogy]]'' \n|-\n| [[Senex iratus]] || A father figure and comic archetype who belongs to the [[alazon]] or impostor group in theater, manifesting himself through his rages and threats, his obsessions and his gullibility || [[Pantalone]], [[Arthur Spooner]], [[Grampa Simpson]]\n|-\n| [[Shrew (archetype)|Shrew]] || A woman given to violent, scolding, particularly nagging treatment of men. || [[Lois Griffin]], [[Wilma Flintstone]]\n|-\n| [[Sinnekins]] || Pairs of devilish, impish characters who exert their perfidious influence on the main character. || [[Flotsam and Jetsam (The Little Mermaid)|Flotsam and Jetsam]], [[List of Disney's Hercules characters#Pain and Panic|Pain and Panic]], [[The Cat in the Hat|Thing Number 1 and Thing Number 2]], [[Winged monkeys]]\n|-\n|Sleazy lawyer|| A corrupt attorney who uses technicalities to get obviously-guilty, but wealthy and well-paying, clients acquitted. Sleazy lawyers are driven by a mixture of desiring wealth and a ruthless, competitive desire to win at all costs. They are masters at manipulating witnesses, D.A.s and judges to ensure they win. They range from lawyers who work within the law, by [[gaming the system]] or finding [[loophole]]s, to those who break the law by destroying evidence or intimidating witnesses.\n||Jerome Facher in ''[[A Civil Action]]'', James Sinclair, Esq. on ''[[NYPD Blue]]'', Martin Vail in ''[[Primal Fear]]'' (1996)\n|-\n|Sleazy politician || An elected official who is embroiled in scandals such as taking bribes, using secret slush funds, embezzling money, or engaging in affairs with staff (or other [[sexual misconduct]]). They may be hypocrites, who speak out against crime, while using illegal drugs and hanging out in brothels. || City Councilman Bill Dexhart of ''Parks and Recreation'', Senator Clay Davis on ''[[The Wire]]'', Mayor Quimby in ''[[The Simpsons]]''\n|-\n| [[Soubrette]] || A female character who is vain, girlish, mischievous, lighthearted, coquettish, and gossipy. || Susanna in ''[[The Marriage of Figaro (play)|The Marriage of Figaro]]'', Gretchen Wieners in ''[[Mean Girls]]'', [[Poison Ivy (character)|Poison Ivy]]\n|-\n| [[Southern belle]] || An elegant, beautiful young woman of the American Old South's upper class. She speaks with a Southern accent and is flirtatious. There is a good, wholesome variant and a vain, darker version. ||[[Scarlett O'Hara]], [[Blanche Dubois]], [[Blanche Devereaux]]\n|-\n| [[Space Nazis]] ||  Antagonists in science fiction works who show totalitarian, militaristic, and genocidal traits reminiscent of [[Nazi]]s|| [[Patterns of Force (Star Trek: The Original Series)|Patterns of Force]]\n|-\n| [[Spear carrier]] || A minor character who appears in several scenes, but mostly in the background roles. The term is a reference to minor characters in old plays set in Roman eras who would literally carry a spear as they played guard characters.|| \n|-\n|Starving artist || An impoverished painter, jazz musician, screenwriter, or novelist who is so dedicated to their artistic vision, that they refuse to [[sell out]] and do commercial art (or pop music, or mainstream feature films, etc). They live in an attic or [[couch surf]], dress shabbily, and struggle to put food on the table. The depiction ranges from a romanticized, [[rose-tinted glasses]] portrait of libertine, [[Absinthe]]-sipping [[Bohemian]]s to a gritty [[social realism|social realist]] examination of the artist's impoverished existence. A starving artist may also be a [[#troubled artist|troubled artist]].||The depiction of [[Jerry Mulligan]] in ''[[An American in Paris]]'', both male leads in ''[[Withnail & I]]'',  Joe Gillis in ''[[Sunset Boulevard]]'', the painter and playwright in ''[[Design for Living]]'', various  [[Bohemian]]s working as actors, artists, and writers in ''[[Moulin Rouge!]]'', Llewyn Davis in ''[[Inside Llewyn Davis]]'' \n|-\n| [[Straight man]]  || A sidekick to a funny person who makes his partner look all the more ridiculous by being completely serious. || [[Oliver Hardy]], [[Bud Abbott]], [[David Mitchell (comedian)|David Mitchell]]\n|-\n| [[Superhero]] || A Noble, brave person with supernatural powers who is dedicated to protecting the public.<ref name=ESF/> || [[Thor (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Thor]], [[Captain Marvel (DC Comics)|Shazam]], [[Sonic the Hedgehog (character)|Sonic the Hedgehog]]\n|-\n| [[Superfluous man]] || In Russian 19th century literature, a dashing young aristocrat who is bored from his privileged life, and who distracts himself from his sense of [[ennui]] by engaging in intrigues, casual affairs, duels, gambling, and drinking. He is selfish and manipulative, and cares little about others or broader issues in society.  ||[[Eugene Onegin]]\n|-\n| [[Supersoldier]] || A soldier who operates beyond human limits or abilities || [[Captain America]], [[Master Chief (Halo)|Master Chief]], [[Bloodshot (comics)|Bloodshot]], [[Universal Soldier]]{{dn|date=April 2020}}\n|-\n| [[Supervillain]] || The nemesis to the Superhero, the supervillain is morally corrupt.|| [[Lex Luthor]], [[Joker (character)|The Joker]], [[Dr. Evil]]\n|-\n| [[Swashbuckler]] || A joyful, noisy, and boastful [[Renaissance era]] swordsman or [[pirate]]. He is chivalrous, courageous, and skilled in swordfighting and acrobatics as he seems vengeance on a corrupt villain. || [[Charles de Batz de Castelmore d'Artagnan|D'Artagnan]], [[Zorro]], [[Jack Sparrow]]\n|-\n!colspan=\"4\" | T\n|-\n| Thug || A henchman or gang member who commits violent crimes || [[Bill Sikes]], [[Trainspotting (novel)#characters|Francis Begbie]], [[Biff Tannen]]\n|-\n| [[Tiger mom]] || A [[Stereotypes of East Asians in the United States|stereotype of East Asian]] mothers who relentlessly push their children to achieve success. Tiger moms set the highest standards and insist that their children strive for top marks so they can get into the best schools. In US TV and movies, this [[ethnic stereotype]] depicts East Asians as a \"[[model minority]]\".|| Bi Sheng Nan in [[Tiger Mom (TV series)|Tiger Mom]]\n|-\n| [[Tomboy]] || A girl or young woman with boyish and/or manly behavior. || [[Merida (Brave)|Merida]], [[Mulan (Disney character)|Mulan]], [[List of My Little Pony: Friendship Is Magic characters#Rainbow Dash|Rainbow Dash]], [[Princess Daisy]]\n|-\n| [[Tortured artist]] || A painter, sculptor, or other creator frustrated with their artistic challenges, or with being misunderstood. They may have mental health issues or addiction, and they are hard to be around due to their narcissism and frustration. || [[List of Spaced characters|Brian Topp]], [[Vincent van Gogh]] \n|-\n| [[Town drunk]] || A male in a small town who is intoxicated more often than sober. They often have a good heart and may end up helping the protagonist. || [[Barney Gumble]], [[Otis Campbell]], [[Matthew Scudder]]\n|-\n| [[Tragic hero]] || A hero with a  flaw that leads to their eventual death and downfall. || [[Michael Corleone]], [[Jay Gatsby]], [[Randle McMurphy]]\n|-\n| [[Tragic mulatto]] || A mulatto who is sad or suicidal because they fail to fit in with white or black people. || Judy Kovacs in the episode ''Are You Now or Have You Ever Been'' in the television series ''[[Angel (1999 TV series)|Angel]]'', Eliza, Cassy, and Emmeline in ''[[Uncle Tom's Cabin]]'', Peola Johnson in ''[[Imitation of Life (1934 film)|Imitation of Life]]''\n|-\n| [[Tsundere]] || In Japanese [[anime]] and [[manga]], a character who is initially cold (and sometimes even hostile) before gradually showing a warmer, friendlier side over time. || [[Asuka Langley Soryu]], Tsuyukusa from ''[[Amatsuki]]''\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\" | U\n|-\n| [[\u00dcbermensch]]<ref name=ESF/> || A (often only seemingly) perfect human being || [[Superman]], [[Hercules]], [[Don Pedro (Much Ado About Nothing)|Don Pedro]]\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\" | V\n|-\n| [[Vice (character)|Vice]] || An allegorical evil part in medieval morality plays. ||\n|-\n| [[Village idiot]] || A person known locally for ignorance or stupidity; this character often turns out to be brave and good, and is sometimes underestimated (see [[Wise fool]]). || [[Michelangelo (Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles)|Michelangelo]], [[Bertie Wooster]], [[Patrick Star]]\n|-\n| [[Villain]]<ref name=ESF/> || An evil character in a story. || [[Shere Khan]], [[Keyser S\u00f6ze]], [[It (character)|Pennywise the Dancing Clown]]\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\" | W\n|-\n| Whisky priest || A priest or ordained minister who shows clear signs of moral weakness, while at the same time teaching a higher standard. || [[Father Callahan]], [[Elmer Gantry]], [[The Power and the Glory|Mexican Priest]] in ''The Power and the Glory'', [[Reverend Harry Powell|Harry Powell]]\n|-\n| [[White hunter]] || Khaki-clad, [[Pith helmet|pith-helmeted]] Caucasian [[big-game hunter]]s or safari leaders in [[Africa]], used to illustrate the Imperial or racist mindset of the colonial era. || [[Allan Quatermain]], [[Kraven the Hunter]]\n|-\n| [[Wise fool]] || A person who seems like an idiot or simpleton, who may speak inarticulate nonsense in one moment, only to later show wisdom later on. The fool's mocking humour shows his ability to understand events or speak blunt truths to a leader. || [[Puck (A Midsummer Night's Dream)|Puck]], [[Goofy]], [[Timon and Pumbaa]]\n|-\n| [[Wise old man]] || An elderly, learned character who provides [[mentoring]] and wisdom to the protagonist. In fantasy, he may also be a [[Wizard (paranormal)|wizard]]. || [[Obi-Wan Kenobi]], [[Albus Dumbledore]], [[Roger Murtaugh]]\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\" | Y\n|-\n| [[Yokel]] || An unsophisticated country person whose rural accent and coarse manners are used for [[comic relief]]. || [[Trevor Philips]], [[Cletus Spuckler]], [[Dale Gribble]]\n|-\n| [[Youxia]] || A Chinese type of the [[Knight-errant]] || [[Fong Sai-yuk]]\n|-\n| [[Yuppie]] || In 1980s and early 1990s films and TV (or works set in that era), a young, urban professional who is driven by their goals of career success and achieving wealth. Typically a lawyer, financial executive, or businessperson, they love their luxury car (a [[Saab]] or [[BMW]]), their house in a trendy downtown neighbourhood, dressing in designer clothes, and eating at hip restaurants. May be depicted as benign for satirical purposes,  or depicted as immoral, villainous profiteers. || [[Trading Places|Louis Winthorpe III]] in ''Trading Places'', Executive Mitch Robbins in ''[[City Slickers]]'', [[Gordon Gekko]] in ''[[Wall Street (film)|Wall Street]]'', [[Patrick Bateman]] in ''[[American Psycho]]''\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Commedia dell'arte]]\n* [[Stereotype]]\n* [[List of stock characters in military fiction]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Stock characters}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of stock characters|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{original research|date=December 2014}}\n{{more citations needed|date=December 2014}}\n}}\n\n{{Expand list|date=December 2009}}\nA '''[[stock character]]''' is a dramatic or literary character representing a generic type in a conventional, simplified manner and recurring in many fictional works.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.oed.com|title=Oxford English Dictionary|accessdate=2008-05-03|postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref>  The following list labels some of these [[stereotype]]s and provides  examples. Some [[Archetypal literary criticism|character archetype]]s, the more universal foundations of fictional characters, are also listed. Some characters that were first introduced as fully fleshed-out characters become subsequently used as stock characters in other works (e.g., the [[Ebenezer Scrooge]] character from ''[[A Christmas Carol]]'', upon whom the miserly Scrooge type is based).\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"\n||'''Character Type'''\n||'''Description'''\n||'''Examples'''\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\" | A\n|-\n| [[Absent-minded professor]] || An eccentric scientific genius who is so focused on their work that they have shortfalls in other areas of life (remembering things, grooming). <ref name=ESF>{{Citation|title=The Encyclopedia of Science Fiction|author=John Clute, Peter Nicholls|publisher=Orbit|year=1993|isbn=1-85723-124-4|postscript=<!--none-->}}</ref> This is the benign version of the [[mad scientist]]. || [[Professor Calculus]], [[Emmett Brown]], [[The Nutty Professor (character)|Sherman Klump]], [[Professor E. Gadd]]\n|-\n|[[Angry Black Woman]] || An assertive, overbearing, opinionated, loud, and \"sassy\" black woman with a sharp tongue, often depicted as nagging and emasculating a male character.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.theroot.com/articles/culture/2014/09/the_angry_black_woman_ stereotype_s_long_history.html |title= Here's Some History Behind That 'Angry Black Woman' Riff the NY Times Tossed Around |date= 25 September 2014 |first= Blair |last= Kelley |work= The Root |accessdate= 24 January 2015 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150121162743/http://www.theroot.com/articles/culture/2014/09/the_angry_black_woman_stereotype_s_long_history.html |archivedate= 21 January 2015 }}</ref> This has been criticized by scholars as a negative stereotype. <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ashley |first1=Wendy |title=The Angry Black Woman: The Impact of Pejorative Stereotypes on Psychotherapy with Black Women |journal=Social Work in Public Health |date=4 November 2013 |volume=29 |issue=1 |pages=27\u201334 |doi=10.1080/19371918.2011.619449 |pmid=24188294 }}</ref>\n|| Sapphire in ''[[Amos 'n' Andy]]'',<ref name=real>{{cite news|title=Find real African American women in a beauty salon, not on reality TV|publisher=Greensboro News & Record|date=November 10, 2013|author=Naeemah Clark}}</ref> Wilhelmina Slater in [[Ugly Betty]],<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kretsedemas|first1=Philip |year=2010 |title='But She's Not Black!' |journal=Journal of African American Studies |volume=14 |issue=2 |pages=149\u2013170 |doi=10.1007/s12111-009-9116-3}}</ref> [[Esther Anderson (Sanford and Son)|Aunt Esther]] \n|-\n| [[Antihero]]\n|A protagonist lacking conventional heroic qualities, such as morality, courage, or idealism.<ref>[http://www.ahdictionary.com/word/search.html?q=Antihero \"American Heritage Dictionary Entry: antihero\"]. Ahdictionary.com. 2013-01-09. Retrieved 2013-10-03.</ref> An antihero has flaws and they may break the law, but they have a good heart.\n| [[Deadpool]], [[Man with No Name]], [[Han Solo]], [[Eddie Valiant]]\n|-\n| [[Author surrogate]] || A character sharing the traits of its author or creator.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Pandey | first = Ashish | year = 2005 | title = Academic Dictionary Of Fiction | publisher = Isha Books | page = 18 | isbn = 8182052629}}</ref> The author surrogate may be disguised to some degree, or there may be little attempt to make them appear different (for example, they may have the same name and job).\n || [[Jon Arbuckle]],  [[Stan Marsh]], [[Kyle Broflovski]]\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\" | B\n|-\n| [[Bad boy (archetype)|Bad boy]] || A roguish, good-looking macho, often a womanizer. In his frequent affairs, he shows a \"[[dark triad]]\" of [[Machiavellianism (psychology)|Machiavellian]] traits. In historical fiction, he is a [[rake (character)|rake]] or cad.|| [[Iron Man|Tony Stark]], [[Gregory House]], [[Danny Zuko]]\n|-\n| [[Bard]]|| A lute-playing [[singer-songwriter]] in Medieval and Rennaissance stories who sings about the events of the day to earn a living. The Bard may be a wandering [[troubador]] travelling from town to town, and playing at taverns (or [[busking]] when gigs are scarce), or they may have a steady job in a noble court, playing for royalty at feasts. The bard may overlap with the [[jester]] if they use their songs to speak blunt truths to a king or entertain the nobles with humour (also providing [[comic relief]] in the story). The bard may also be a wandering minstrel who voyages with the hero to chronicle the hero's exploits in song.||Cantus in ''[[Fraggle Rock]]'', Marillion in ''[[Game of Thrones]]'', Jaskier in ''[[The Witcher (TV series)|The Witcher]]'', Gabrielle from ''[[Xena: Warrior Princess]]'' \n|-\n| [[Battle-axe (woman)|Battle-axe]] || An old, domineering, brash and brazen woman ||  [[List of recurring Simpsons characters#Agnes Skinner|Agnes Skinner]], [[Thelma Harper]], [[List of Everybody Loves Raymond characters#Marie Barone|Marie Barone]]\n|-\n| [[Black knight]] || An evil fighter antagonist, whose identify is often concealed behind his visor. He may be associated with death. He battles the good [[knight-errant]].  || [[Black Knight (Monty Python)|Black Knight]], [[Black Knight (Nathan Garrett)|Nathan Garrett]], [[Darth Vader]]\n|-\n|Blind seer || A mystic who is sightless, but uses spiritual or psychic powers to sense the events and sights around them.|| [[Rogue One|Chirrut]] in ''Rogue One'', [[The Book of Eli|Eli]], [[Zatoichi]] (blind swordsman)\n|-\n| [[Boy next door (stock character)|Boy next door]] || An average and nice guy who is reasonably good-looking || [[Marty McFly]], [[Luke Skywalker]], [[Spider-Man|Peter Parker]]\n|-\n| [[Bug-eyed monster]] || A staple evil alien<ref name=ESF/> || [[Formics]], [[Alien (creature in Alien franchise)|Alien]]\n|-\n!colspan=\"4\" | C\n|-\n| [[Cat lady]] || An eccentric, lonely woman, often living alone. She may be depicted as dotty and benevolent or as unhinged. || [[Crazy Cat Lady]], [[Arabella Figg]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone|last=Rowling|first=J.K.|publisher=Bloomsbury|date=26 June 1997|isbn=0-7475-3269-9|location=United Kingdom|pages=}}</ref> [[Angela Martin]]\n|-\n|[[Chosen One (Star Wars)|Chosen one]] || A person selected for having a rare skill or ability that will enable them to save the world. || [[Rey (Star Wars)|Rey]], [[Anakin Skywalker]], [[Neo (The Matrix)]]\n|-\n| [[Con artist]] || A person who tricks people out of money by gaining, and then betraying their confidence. || [[Del Boy]], [[Artful Dodger]], [[Danny Ocean (character)|Danny Ocean]], [[Wario]]\n|-\n| Contender || A competitive, scrappy underdog who is driven to keep trying to win. || [[Rocky Balboa]], [[Lightning McQueen]], [[Daniel LaRusso]], [[Little Mac]]\n|-\n|Career criminal\n|Often a cunning thief. Has a strange gait, slouched posture and devious facial expression. \n|[[Flynn Rider]], [[Bernie Rhodenbarr]], [[Burglar (comics)|Cash Register Thief]]\n|-\n| [[Crone]] || A cruel, withered old woman, often occult or witch-like. || [[Baba Yaga]], [[Wicked Witch of the West]], [[Maleficent]], [[Gruntilda]]\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\" | D\n|-\n| [[Damsel in distress]] || A noble, beautiful young Lady in need of rescue, traditionally from dragons. In early 1900s films, she is threatened by a robber or kidnapper. || [[Princess Peach]], [[Princess Zelda]], [[Daphne Blake]] \n|-\n| [[Dandy]] || A good-looking, well-off young man more interested in fashion and leisure than business and politics. Prominent in Victorian writings. || [[Dorian Gray]], [[Hercule Poirot]], [[Psmith]]\n|-\n| Dark Lady || A dark, malicious or doomed woman || [[Lady Macbeth]], [[Miss Trunchbull]], [[Annie Wilkes]]\n|-\n| [[Dark Lord (fiction)|Dark Lord]] || An evil, powerful, often godlike or near-immortal sorcerer. The dark lord is often wounded, though still powerful enough to  defile the land. He may be a [[Devil]] archetype. || [[Palpatine]], [[Lord Voldemort]], [[Thanos]]\n|-\n| Dastardly Whiplash || A classic [[villain]] archetype from the [[silent film]] era, who will tie a [[damsel in distress|maiden]] to train tracks or burn down an orphanage as part of their schemes, all while twirling a long mustache. They have over-the-top personalities. || [[Dick Dastardly]], [[King K. Rool]], [[Robbie Rotten]]\n|-\n| [[Dragon lady]] || A [[Stereotypes of East Asians in the United States|stereotype of East Asian]] and occasionally [[Stereotypes of South Asians|South Asian]] and [[Southeast Asia]]n women as strong, deceitful, domineering, or mysterious.<ref name=\"Herbst\">{{cite book |last=Herbst |first=Philip |title=The color of words: An encyclopaedic dictionary of ethnic bias in the United States |publisher=Intercultural Press |year=1997 |page=72|isbn=978-1-877864-97-1}}</ref> The term's origin and usage arose in America during the late 1800s.<ref name=\":0\" /> This [[ethnic stereotype]] may negatively depict women as promiscuous, deceptive [[femme fatale]]s.|| [[Tomorrow Never Dies|Michelle Yeoh]]'s character in ''Tomorrow Never Dies''\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\" | E\n|-\n| [[Elderly martial arts master]] || A wise old man mentoring a young disciple in his ancient craft. The old man often needs to be avenged. || [[Mr. Miyagi]], [[Ra's al Ghul]], [[Yoda]], [[Splinter (Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles)|Splinter]]\n|-\n| [[Everyman]] || An ordinary, humble individual, the Everyman may be a [[Audience surrogate|stand-in for the audience]] or reader. || [[Arthur Dent]], [[Homer Simpson]], [[Tim Canterbury]]\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\" | F\n|-\n| [[Fall guy]] || An unaware scapegoat for a villain's larger plot. ||[[Alex Parrish]], [[The Maltese Falcon (1941 film)|Wilmer Cook]], [[The Strawberry Blonde|Biff]] from ''The Strawberry Blonde''\n|-\n| [[Farmer's daughter (character)|Farmer's daughter]] || A desirable, wholesome, and naive young woman, also described as being an \"open-air type\" and \"public-spirited\"<ref name=Wood2006 >{{citation | last=Wood | first=Robin | year=2006 | title=Howard Hawks | publisher=Wayne State University Press | isbn=978-0-8143-3276-4  | page=30 | url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=lh655HlOlNQC }}</ref><ref name=\"KohlkeOrza2008\">{{cite book|author1=Marie-Luise Kohlke|author2=Luisa Orza|title=Negotiating sexual idioms: image, text, performance|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0lFBBEeLx9UC|accessdate=9 June 2011|date=22 October 2008|publisher=Rodopi|isbn=978-90-420-2491-5}}</ref> || [[The Silence of the Clamps|Crushinator]]\n|-\n| [[Femme fatale]] || A beautiful, alluring, woman who is also traitorous, cunning and deceptive. She draws men into a [[honey trap]]. ||[[The Maltese Falcon (1941 film)|Ruth Wonderly]], [[Poison Ivy (comics)|Poison Ivy]], [[Salome]], [[Basic Instinct|Catherine Trammel]]\n|-\n| [[Final girl]] || A \"last woman standing\" left in a horror film after a killer or monster has eliminated her companions. || [[Mina Harker]], [[Laurie Strode]], [[Sally Hardesty]]\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\" | G\n|-\n|[[Geek]]|| An [[Eccentricity (behavior)|eccentric]] or non-mainstream person who is an expert or [[enthusiast]] obsessed with a hobby or [[intellectual]] pursuit, with a general [[pejorative]] meaning of a \"peculiar person, especially one who is perceived to be overly intellectual, unfashionable, boring, or socially awkward\".<ref name=\"merriam-webster\">{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/geek|title=Geek|date=|accessdate=January 2, 2016 |work=Dictionary.com-Merriam-Webster entry}}</ref> The geek character overlaps with the [[nerd]], but the geek may be depicted in a more negative fashion.|| [[Sheldon Cooper]] in ''[[The Big Bang Theory]]''\n|-\n|Gentle giant|| A huge, strong man who, despite his fear-inspiring appearance, has a good heart. || [[The Princess Bride|Fezzick]], [[Kronk]], [[Chunky Kong]]\n|-\n| [[Gentleman thief]] || A sophisticated, well-mannered, and elegant thief. He typically tries to avoid violence by using deception and his wits to steal. || [[Kaito Kuroba]], [[Sly Cooper (character)|Sly Cooper]], [[Neal Caffrey]] from ''[[Heat (1995 film)|Heat]]''\n|-\n| [[Girl next door]] || An average young woman, reasonably attractive, with a wholesome demeanor.|| [[Rachel Green]], [[Carrie Bradshaw]], [[Bridget Jones]]\n|-\n| Grande dame || [[French language|French]] for \"great lady\"; a haughty, flamboyant and elegant woman, prone to extravagant and eccentric fashion. She is usually a [[stereotype]] of an elderly [[Upper class|high society]] [[socialite]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fodors.com/community/united-states/in-search-of-old-grand-dame-style-new-england-hotels.cfm |title=In search of old, grand-dame style New England hotels &#124; United States Forum &#124; Fodor's Travel Talk Forums |publisher=Fodors.com |date= |accessdate=2013-09-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cntraveller.com/guides/europe/england/london/where-to-stay/the-lanesborough |title=Where to Stay in London - Best Hotels & Travel Guide (Cond\u00e9 Nast Traveller) |publisher=Cntraveller.com |date=2012-08-29 |accessdate=2013-09-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Bean |first=Kitty |url=https://www.usatoday.com/travel/hotels/2007-11-29-grande-dames_N.htm |title=Grande-dame hotels unveiling fresh faces |newspaper=USA Today |date=2007-11-30 |accessdate=2013-09-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://wanderlustandlipstick.com/blogs/travelpurpose/2011/02/09/torontos-fairmont-royal-york-hotel-the-grande-dame-walks-her-talk/ |title=Toronto\u2019s Fairmont Royal York Hotel: The Grande Dame Walks Her Talk - Travel with a Purpose - Travel with a Purpose |publisher=Wanderlustandlipstick.com |date=2011-02-09 |accessdate=2013-09-02}}</ref> || Constance in ''[[Gosford Park]]'', Princess Dragomiroff in ''[[Murder on the Orient Express]]''; Lady Bracknell in ''[[The Importance of Being Earnest]]''\n|-\n|Grotesque || A deformed or disabled person whose appearance scares strangers or inspires pity, and who may be mistreated. He is a tragic figure. || [[Hunchback of Notre Dame]]\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\" | H\n|-\n| [[Hag]] || A wizened, withered, and bitter old woman, often a malicious witch. || [[Baba Yaga]], [[Evil Queen (Disney)|Wicked Queen]], [[Gruntilda]]\n|-\n|[[Hardboiled|Hardboiled detective]]\n|| A private investigator or police officer rendered bitter and cynical by violence and  corruption. They are often hard-drinking [[antihero]]es who use  questionable tactics. Typically the protagonist in [[film noir]] crime movies and [[hardboiled]] novels and [[pulp magazine|pulp fiction]].\n|| [[Philip Marlowe]], [[Mike Hammer]], [[Sam Spade]]\n|-\n| [[Harlequin]] || A clown or professional [[fool]]{{dn|date=April 2020}} who pokes fun at others, even the elite. || [[Till Eulenspiegel]], [[Krusty the Clown]]\n|-\n| [[Hooker with a heart of gold]] || A prostitute who has a good moral compass and intrinsic morality.|| [[Nancy (Oliver Twist)|Nancy]], [[Fantine]], [[Inara Serra]]\n|-\n|Hopeless romantic\n|A loving, passionate character that often finds \"love at first sight\". He is obsessive over a romantic partner (or love interest), usually views life very optimistically. ||\n[[Humphrey Goodman]], [[Walden Schmidt]], [[Brian Griffin]]\n|-\n|[[Housewife]]\n|A busy mother of the protagonist family, she takes care of the children and does the housework. Her appearance ranges from homely to average.\n|[[Morticia Addams]], [[Jane Jetson]], [[Marge Simpson]]\n|-\n| Hotshot || A reckless, impulsive macho character known for taking risks.|| [[Martin Riggs]], [[Agent J]], [[Axel Foley]]\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\" | I\n|-\n| [[Idiot savant]] || A person with extraordinary genius in a narrow area who has a social or developmental disability.|| [[Forrest Gump (character)|Forrest Gump]], [[Rain Man|Raymond \"Rain Man\" Babbitt]]\n|-\n| [[Ingenue (stock character)|Ingenue]] || An attractive young woman who is endearingly innocent and wholesome. || [[Ariel (The Little Mermaid)|Ariel]], [[Snow White]], [[Dorothy Gale]]\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\" | J\n|-\n| [[Jock (athlete)]] || A male athlete who is often muscular, but not very smart. He may also be a [[bully]]. || [[Flash Thompson]], [[Nathan Scott]], [[Luke Ward]]\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\" | K\n|-\n| [[Knight-errant]] || A noble [[Knight]] on a [[quest]] for his Lady or who is seeking some [[Holy Grail]]. He expresses his [[courtly love]] for his beloved from afar.|| [[Lancelot]], [[Aragorn]], [[Bronn (character)|Bronn]]\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\" | L\n|-\n| [[Little Green Men]] || Small humanoid extraterrestrials with green skin and antennae on their heads;<ref name=TES>{{citation |url=http://www.tes.co.uk/article.aspx?storycode=302196 |publisher=Times Educational Supplement |title=The Planet of the Zogs |date=22 May 1998 |author=Peter Graham |postscript=<!--none-->}}</ref> known familiarly in [[science fiction fandom]] as LGM || [[The Great Gazoo]]\n|-\n| [[Loathly lady]] || A woman who appears to be hideous, often cursed. || ''[[The Wife of Bath's Tale]]''\n|-\n|Loner || An isolated person who struggles to connect with people.|| [[Rebel Without a Cause|James Dean in ''Rebel Without a Cause'']]\n|-\n| [[Lovers (stock characters)|Lovers]] || Main characters who deeply fall in love, despite the blocking effect of other characters or events; often [[moonstruck]], [[star-crossed]] lovers that are strongly fraternizing with the \"enemy\". They may face a tragic end. || [[Romeo & Juliet]]\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\" | M\n|-\n| [[Mad scientist]] || An insane or eccentric scientist or professor, often villainous or amoral.<ref name=ESF/><ref>{{citation |title=Science-fiction Handbook: The Writing of Imaginative Fiction |page=28 |author= De Camp, L. Sprague |year=1953 |postscript=<!--none-->}}</ref> Not all mad scientists are evil; some intend to be benevolent, but unintentionally cause an accident due to their [[hubris]]tic attempt to [[play God]] in the lab. May have an [[Igor (character)|Igor]], a hunchbacked assistant. || [[Victor Frankenstein]], [[Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde (character)|Dr. Henry Jekyll]], [[The Island of Doctor Moreau|Dr. Moreau]]\n|-\n| [[Magical Negro]] || A black man with special insight or mystical powers, who ends up coming to the aid of the white protagonist. || [[Uncle Remus]] \n|-\n| [[Mammy archetype]] || A rotund, homely, and matronly black woman. She has a sunny demeanor. || [[Aunt Jemima]], [[Mammy Two Shoes]], Calpurnia in ''[[To Kill a Mockingbird]]''\n|-\n| [[Manic Pixie Dream Girl]] || Usually static young female characters who have eccentric personality quirks and are unabashedly girlish and dreamy.|| [[Zelda Spellman]], [[Bo Peep (Toy Story)|Bo Peep]]\n|-\n|[[Queen bee (sociology)#Schools|Mean Popular Girl]]\n|An attractive teenage girl who has high status at her school, but is often mean to less popular and less good-looking or lower-status girls.\n|Chlo\u00e9 Bourgeois in ''[[Miraculous: Tales of Ladybug & Cat Noir|Miraculous: Tales of Ladybug and Cat Noir]]'', Nina Harper in ''[[Braceface]]'', Regina George in ''[[Mean Girls]]''\n|-\n| [[Miles Gloriosus]] || A boastful soldier (originally from the comic theatre of ancient Rome) || [[Falstaff]], [[Baron Munchausen]], [[Buzz Lightyear]]\n|-\n| [[Mother's boy]] || An awkward man who is excessively attached to his mother. Often he continues to act in a childish, submissive fashion even into adulthood. || [[Private Pike]], [[Howard Wolowitz]], [[Norman Bates]]\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\" | N\n|-\n| [[Nerd]] || A socially-awkward, obsessive, or overly-intellectual person. They are often interested in doing well in school (academically and in terms of behavior). They tend to dress in unfashionable clothes. The [[geek]] character is similar, but may be depicted in more negative manner. || [[Will McKenzie]], [[Steve Urkel]], [[Hermione Granger]]\n|-\n| [[Nice guy]] || A male character of wholesome morals, agreeable personality and usually modest means who may struggle 