e Chicago Osteopathic Hospital, where she died on 26 April 1942 after a long illness.<ref name=\":0\" /> Her memorial service was held at Chicago's First Unitarian Church, conducted by Dr. Von Ogden Vogt.<ref name=\":2\" /> She was buried at [[Forest Hills Cemetery]] in [[Jamaica Plain]], Massachusetts.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n=== Legacy ===\nAfter her death, Ayscough's correspondence with her friend, the poet [[Amy Lowell]], was compiled and published by her husband Professor Harley Farnsworth MacNair.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hillbrook|first=R|date=1946|title=Florence ayscough and amy lowell|url=|journal=Current History (Pre-1986)|volume=10|pages=445|via=}}</ref> The following year he published a biography of his wife titled ''The Incomparable Lady''.<ref name=\":0\" /> He donated her collection of 1,292 Chinese language books to the [[Library of Congress]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ayscough, Florence}}\n[[Category:Sinologists]]\n[[Category:Women academics]]\n[[Category:Chinese\u2013English translators]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago faculty]]\n[[Category:Writers from Shanghai]]\n[[Category:1942 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century women writers]]\n[[Category:Educators from Shanghai]]\n[[Category:1878 births]]\n", "name_user": "CWH", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life:link HF MacNair", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Florence_Ayscough"}
{"title_page": "Rita Sanders Geier", "text_new": "Rita Sanders Geier (nee Rita Sanders) is a civil right pioneer and Commissioner of Social Security Administration. As a professor at Tennessee State University, she was the original plaintiff in a landmark that lead to the integration of higher education in the State of Tennessee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov/archive/opa/pr/1997/December97/513cr.htm.html|title=#513 12-7-97 - ATTORNEY GENERAL JANET RENO AND BILL LANN LEE TO COMMEMORATE THE 40TH ANNIVERSARY OF THE CIVIL RIGHTS DIVISION|website=www.justice.gov|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite news|last=Martin|first=Douglas|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/31/us/george-e-barrett-a-tennessee-lawyer-who-fought-for-desegregation-dies-at-86.html|title=George Barrett, Tennessee Lawyer Who Fought for Desegregation, Dies at 86|date=2014-08-30|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-11|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n=== Early Life and Education ===\nGeier was born in Memphis, Tennessee in 1944 to Edwin and Jessie Sanders. Her father was a Methodist minister, and her mother taught public school. In the course of Sanders\u2019s ministry, the family moved to several cities in Arkansas and Tennessee.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://alumnus.tennessee.edu/2007/to-do-the-right-thing/|title=To Do the Right Thing|last=alumn_admin|date=2007-04-01|website=Tennessee Alumnus|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> In 1961, Geier graduated from the segregated Melrose High School in Memphis.Grier holds a law degree from [[Vanderbilt University]] and a master\u2019s from the [[University of Chicago]]. She married her husband, Paul, in 1970. The couple lives in Maryland and has two grown sons, Chris and Jon.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Career ===\n<br />\n\n=== Lawsuit against University of Tennessee ===\nIn 1968, Grier sued the Governor of Tennessee, the University of Tennessee, Tennessee A & I State University, and various Tennessee education agencies and officials to enjoin UT from expanding its program at a non-degree granting center in Nashville. The complaint alleged that any expansion of UT-N would affect the efforts of [[Tennessee State University]], a predominantly black institution, to desegregate its student body and faculty. Subsequently, the case became a vehicle for the desegregation of state-affiliated colleges and universities in Tennessee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F3/94/644/602579/|title=Rita Sanders Geier, et al., Plaintiffs-appellees,united States of America, Plaintiff Intervenor-appellee,raymond A. Richardson, Jr., et al., Plaintiffs Intervenors-appellees, v. Don Sundquist, et al., Defendants,tennessee State University National Alumni Association,intervention-appellant, 94 F.3d 644 (6th Cir. 1996)|website=Justia Law|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nThe United States intervened as a plaintiff in 1968. In 1973, a group of parents, teachers, and faculty members (\"Richardson Intervenors\") were allowed to intervene. In 1983, the district court allowed another group of black and white TSU faculty members and students to intervene (\"McGinnis Intervenors\"). Also in 1983, the district court allowed the Alumni Association, which consists of graduates of TSU, to appear as amicus curiae.\n\nIn 1984, all of the parties except the United States agreed to a settlement agreement (\"Settlement\"), which the district court entered as an order. The Settlement was affirmed in Geier v. Alexander, 801 F.2d 799 (6th Cir. 1986). Under the Settlement, defendants agreed to promote system-wide desegregation by a variety of means including (1) attempting to obtain a student body at TSU that is 50% white; (2) assuring that changes in admissions policies do not have adverse racial impact; and (3) actively recruiting African-American faculty and administrative staff for Tennessee's predominantly white institutions.\n\n=== References ===\n", "text_old": "Rita Sanders Geier (nee Rita Sanders) is a civil right pioneer and Commissioner of Social Security Administration. As a professor at Tennessee State University, she fought against segregation of the school for more than 38 years.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Martin|first=Douglas|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/31/us/george-e-barrett-a-tennessee-lawyer-who-fought-for-desegregation-dies-at-86.html|title=George Barrett, Tennessee Lawyer Who Fought for Desegregation, Dies at 86|date=2014-08-30|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-11|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n=== Early Life and Education ===\nGeier was born in Memphis, Tennessee in 1944 to Edwin and Jessie Sanders. Her father was a Methodist minister, and her mother taught public school. In the course of Sanders\u2019s ministry, the family moved to several cities in Arkansas and Tennessee.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://alumnus.tennessee.edu/2007/to-do-the-right-thing/|title=To Do the Right Thing|last=alumn_admin|date=2007-04-01|website=Tennessee Alumnus|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> In 1961, Geier graduated from the segregated Melrose High School in Memphis.Grier holds a law degree from [[Vanderbilt University]] and a master\u2019s from the [[University of Chicago]]. She married her husband, Paul, in 1970. The couple lives in Maryland and has two grown sons, Chris and Jon.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Career ===\n<br />\n\n=== Lawsuit against University of Tennessee ===\nIn 1968, Grier sued the Governor of Tennessee, the University of Tennessee, Tennessee A & I State University, and various Tennessee education agencies and officials to enjoin UT from expanding its program at a non-degree granting center in Nashville. The complaint alleged that any expansion of UT-N would affect the efforts of [[Tennessee State University]], a predominantly black institution, to desegregate its student body and faculty. Subsequently, the case became a vehicle for the desegregation of state-affiliated colleges and universities in Tennessee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F3/94/644/602579/|title=Rita Sanders Geier, et al., Plaintiffs-appellees,united States of America, Plaintiff Intervenor-appellee,raymond A. Richardson, Jr., et al., Plaintiffs Intervenors-appellees, v. Don Sundquist, et al., Defendants,tennessee State University National Alumni Association,intervention-appellant, 94 F.3d 644 (6th Cir. 1996)|website=Justia Law|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nThe United States intervened as a plaintiff in 1968. In 1973, a group of parents, teachers, and faculty members (\"Richardson Intervenors\") were allowed to intervene. In 1983, the district court allowed another group of black and white TSU faculty members and students to intervene (\"McGinnis Intervenors\"). Also in 1983, the district court allowed the Alumni Association, which consists of graduates of TSU, to appear as amicus curiae.\n\nIn 1984, all of the parties except the United States agreed to a settlement agreement (\"Settlement\"), which the district court entered as an order. The Settlement was affirmed in Geier v. Alexander, 801 F.2d 799 (6th Cir. 1986). Under the Settlement, defendants agreed to promote system-wide desegregation by a variety of means including (1) attempting to obtain a student body at TSU that is 50% white; (2) assuring that changes in admissions policies do not have adverse racial impact; and (3) actively recruiting African-American faculty and administrative staff for Tennessee's predominantly white institutions.\n\n=== References ===\n", "name_user": "ThePhantom65", "label": "safe", "comment": "added content and citations", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rita_Sanders_Geier"}
{"title_page": "Zond 8", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox spaceflight\n| name                  = Zond 8\n| names_list            = \n\n<!--image of the spacecraft/mission-->\n| image                 = Zond L1 drawing.png\n| image_caption         = A drawing of Zond 8 spacecraft.\n| image_alt             = \n| image_size            = 175px\n\n<!--Basic details-->\n| mission_type          = Spacecraft test\n| operator              = [[TsKBEM]]\n| COSPAR_ID             = 1970-088A\n| SATCAT                = 04591\n| mission_duration      = 7 days\n| distance_travelled    = \n| orbits_completed      = \n\n<!--Spacecraft properties-->\n| spacecraft            = Soyuz 7K-L1 s/n 14 \n| spacecraft_type       = [[Human spaceflight|Uncrewed version]]\n| spacecraft_bus        = [[Soyuz 7K-L1]]\n| manufacturer          = [[OKB-1]]\n\n| launch_mass           = 5375 kg <ref name=\"Cosmos\"/>\n| landing_mass          = \n| dry_mass              = \n| payload_mass          = \n| dimensions            = \n| power                 = \n\n<!--Launch details-->\n| launch_date           = 20 October 1970<br/>19:55:39 GMT <ref name=\"Trajectory\"/>\n| launch_rocket         = [[Proton-K]] / [[Blok D]]\n| launch_site           = [[Baikonur Cosmodrome]]<br/>[[Baikonur Cosmodrome|Site 81/23]]\n| launch_contractor     = [[OKB-1]]\n\n<!--end of mission-->\n| disposal_type         = \n| deactivated           = \n| destroyed             = \n| last_contact          = \n| recovery_by           = Soviet recovery vessel ''Taman''\n| recovery_date         = 27 October 1970 ([[Indian Ocean]])\n| decay_date            = \n| landing_date          = 27 October 1970, 13:55 GMT <ref>https://www.nasa.gov/sites/default/files/atoms/files/beyond-earth-tagged.pdf</ref>\n| landing_site          = [[Chagos Archipelago]]<br/>(730 km at SE) <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://epizodsspace.airbase.ru/bibl/inostr-yazyki/sov-luna/sovets-luna.pdf|title=Soviet and Russian Lunar Exploration |last=|first=|date=|website=|page=314|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n<!--orbit parameters-->\n| orbit_reference       = [[Geocentric orbit|Geocentric]]\n| orbit_regime          = Circumlunar \n| orbit_longitude       = <!--geosynchronous satellites only-->\n| orbit_periapsis       = <!--periapsis altitude--> \n| orbit_apoapsis        = <!--apoapsis altitude--> \n| orbit_inclination     = <!--orbital inclination--> \n| orbit_period          = <!--time taken to complete an orbit-->\n| orbit_epoch           = <!--the date at which the orbit parameters were correct-->\n| orbit_rev_number      = <!--revolution number-->\n| apsis                 = gee\n\n|interplanetary         = <!--Infobox spaceflight/IP can be called multiple times for missions with multiple targets or combined orbiter/lander missions, etc-->\n {{Infobox spaceflight/IP\n   |type                = flyby\n   |object              = [[Moon]]\n   |orbits              = \n   |arrival_date        = 24 October 1970\n   |departure_date      = \n   |location            = \n   |distance            = 1110 km\n   |sample_mass         = \n   \n }}\n\n<!--transponder parameters-->\n| trans_band            = <!--Transponder frequency bands-->\n| trans_frequency       = <!--specific frequencies-->\n| trans_bandwidth       = <!--bandwidth-->\n| trans_capacity        = <!--capacity of the transponders-->\n| trans_coverage        = <!--area covered-->\n\n<!--Only use where a spacecraft/mission is part of a clear programme of sequential missions. \n| programme             = \n| previous_mission      =\n| next_mission          =\n\n<!--mission insignia or patch-->\n| insignia              = <!--omit the \"file\" prefix-->\n| insignia_caption      = <!--image caption-->\n| insignia_alt          = <!--image alt text-->\n| insignia_size         = <!--include px/em; defaults to 180px-->\n}}\n\n'''Zond 8''', was the last in the series of circumlunar spacecraft, a member of the Soviet [[Zond program]], designed to rehearse a piloted circumlunar flight, an uncrewed version of [[Soyuz 7K-L1]] crewed circumlunar flight spacecraft. The project was initiated in 1965 to compete with the Americans in the race to the Moon but lost its importance once three astronauts circled the Moon on the [[Apollo 8]] mission in December 1968.\n\n==Mission==\nZond 8 was launched on 20 October 1970, at 19:55:39 GMT by a [[Proton-K]] / [[Blok D]] launcher since the [[Baikonur Cosmodrome|Site 81/23]] of the [[Baikonur Cosmodrome]], towards the [[Moon]], from an Earth-orbiting platform, [[Tyazheliy Sputnik]] (1970-088B). Zond 8 had a mass of {{convert|5375|kg}}.<ref name=\"Cosmos\">{{cite web|title=Zond 8: Display 1970-088A |url=https://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/spacecraft/display.action?id=1967-021A|website=nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov|publisher=NASA|date=27 February 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020}} {{PD-notice}}</ref> The announced objectives of Zond 8 were investigations of the Moon and circumlunar space and testing of onboard systems and units.<ref name=\"Trajectory\">{{cite web|title=Zond 8: Trajectory 1970-088A\n|url=https://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/spacecraft/displayTrajectory.action?id=1970-088A|website=nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov|publisher=NASA|date=27 February 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe spacecraft obtained photographs of Earth on 21 October from a distance of {{convert|64480|km}}. After a mid-course correction on 22 October 1970 at a distance of {{convert|250000|km}} from Earth. The spacecraft transmitted flight images of Earth for three days. Zond 8 reached the Moon without any apparent problems, circling its target on 24 October at a range of {{convert|1110|km}} and took both [[black-and-white]] and [[Color photography|color photographs]] of the lunar surface during two separate sessions.<ref name=\"Experiment\">{{cite web|title=Zond 8: Experiments 1970-088A |url=https://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/spacecraft/displayExperiment.action?spacecraftId=1970-088A|website=nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov|publisher=NASA|date=27 February 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> Scientific measurements were also obtained during the flight.<ref name=\"Deep Space\">{{cite web|last1=Siddiqi|first1=Asif A.|title=Beyond Earth: A Chronicle of Deep Space Exploration, 1958\u20132016|url=https://www.nasa.gov/sites/default/files/atoms/files/beyond-earth-tagged.pdf|publisher=NASA|date=2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter two mid-course corrections on the return leg, Zond 8 achieved a return trajectory over Earth's northern hemisphere instead of the standard southern approach profile, allowing Soviet ground control stations to maintain near-continuous contact with the craft. The guidance system, however, malfunctioned on the return leg, and the spacecraft performed a simple ballistic (instead of a guided) reentry into Earth's atmosphere.<ref name=\"Deep Space\"/>\n\nZond 8 descent module reentered the Earth's atmosphere and splashed down safely in the Indian Ocean at 13:55 GMT on 27 October 1970 at {{convert|730|km}} southeast of the Chagos Islands, {{convert|24|km}} from its original target point. The USSR recovery ship ''Taman'' was on hand to collect it and bring it back to Moscow.<ref name=\"Deep Space\"/>\n\n===Scientific instruments===\n* Imaging system\n* Solar wind collector packages\n\n==Zond 9==\nZond 9, Soyuz 7K-L1 s/n 10, was planned but cancelled. Zond 9 was planned to launch on July of 1969, carrying a crew of [[Pavel Popovich]] and [[Vitali Sevastyanov]], but never flew.<ref>[https://slideplayer.com/slide/12123170/ Soviet Manned Lunar Exploration Program]</ref>\n\n==Zond 10==\nZond 10, Soyuz 7K-L1 s/n 15, was planned but cancelled.<ref>[https://www.globalsecurity.org/space/world/russia/lunar-l-1.htm globalsecurity.org L-1 Lunar Circumnavigation Mission]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Spaceflight}}\n\n* [[Splashdown (spacecraft landing)]]\n* [[Timeline of artificial satellites and space probes]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.mentallandscape.com/C_CatalogMoon.htm Soviet Lunar Images]\n* [https://archive.today/20120719105138/http://www.astronautix.com/craft/soyz7kl1.htm Astronautix.com - detailed on Soyuz 7K-L1 (Zond) program ]\n* {{APOD |date=16 July 2013 |title=The Moon from Zond 8}}\n\n{{Zond program}}\n{{Moon spacecraft}}\n{{N1-L3}}\n{{Orbital launches in 1970}}\n\n[[Category:Missions to the Moon]]\n[[Category:Zond program]]\n[[Category:1970 in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched in 1970]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft which reentered in 1970]]\n[[Category:Lunar flybys]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox spaceflight\n| name                  = Zond 8\n| names_list            = \n\n<!--image of the spacecraft/mission-->\n| image                 = Zond L1 drawing.png\n| image_caption         = Zond 8\n| image_alt             = \n| image_size            = 175px\n\n<!--Basic details-->\n| mission_type          = Spacecraft test\n| operator              = [[TsKBEM]]\n| COSPAR_ID             = 1970-088A\n| SATCAT                = 04591\n| mission_duration      = 7 days\n| distance_travelled    = \n| orbits_completed      = \n\n<!--Spacecraft properties-->\n| spacecraft            = Soyuz 7K-L1 s/n 14 \n| spacecraft_type       = [[Human spaceflight|Uncrewed version]]\n| spacecraft_bus        = [[Soyuz 7K-L1]]\n| manufacturer          = [[OKB-1]]\n\n| launch_mass           = 5375 kg <ref name=\"Cosmos\"/>\n| landing_mass          = \n| dry_mass              = \n| payload_mass          = \n| dimensions            = \n| power                 = \n\n<!--Launch details-->\n| launch_date           = 20 October 1970<br/>19:55:39 GMT <ref name=\"Trajectory\"/>\n| launch_rocket         = [[Proton-K]] / [[Blok D]]\n| launch_site           = [[Baikonur Cosmodrome]]<br/>[[Baikonur Cosmodrome|Site 81/23]]\n| launch_contractor     = [[OKB-1]]\n\n<!--end of mission-->\n| disposal_type         = \n| deactivated           = \n| destroyed             = \n| last_contact          = \n| recovery_by           = Soviet recovery vessel ''Taman''\n| recovery_date         = 27 October 1970 ([[Indian Ocean]])\n| decay_date            = \n| landing_date          = 27 October 1970, 13:55 GMT <ref>https://www.nasa.gov/sites/default/files/atoms/files/beyond-earth-tagged.pdf</ref>\n| landing_site          = [[Chagos Archipelago]]<br/>(730 km at SE) <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://epizodsspace.airbase.ru/bibl/inostr-yazyki/sov-luna/sovets-luna.pdf|title=Soviet and Russian Lunar Exploration |last=|first=|date=|website=|page=314|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n<!--orbit parameters-->\n| orbit_reference       = [[Geocentric orbit|Geocentric]]\n| orbit_regime          = Circumlunar \n| orbit_longitude       = <!--geosynchronous satellites only-->\n| orbit_periapsis       = <!--periapsis altitude--> \n| orbit_apoapsis        = <!--apoapsis altitude--> \n| orbit_inclination     = <!--orbital inclination--> \n| orbit_period          = <!--time taken to complete an orbit-->\n| orbit_epoch           = <!--the date at which the orbit parameters were correct-->\n| orbit_rev_number      = <!--revolution number-->\n| apsis                 = gee\n\n|interplanetary         = <!--Infobox spaceflight/IP can be called multiple times for missions with multiple targets or combined orbiter/lander missions, etc-->\n {{Infobox spaceflight/IP\n   |type                = flyby\n   |object              = [[Moon]]\n   |orbits              = \n   |arrival_date        = 24 October 1970\n   |departure_date      = \n   |location            = \n   |distance            = 1110 km\n   |sample_mass         = \n   \n }}\n\n<!--transponder parameters-->\n| trans_band            = <!--Transponder frequency bands-->\n| trans_frequency       = <!--specific frequencies-->\n| trans_bandwidth       = <!--bandwidth-->\n| trans_capacity        = <!--capacity of the transponders-->\n| trans_coverage        = <!--area covered-->\n\n<!--Only use where a spacecraft/mission is part of a clear programme of 